    "oracle-summons": {
      "id": "oracle-summons",
      "text": "The morning sun rises over the white marble temple of Delphi, perched high on Mount Parnassus. {{BOTH_NAMES}} stand before the Oracle, a mysterious priestess who speaks for the god Apollo.\n\n\"Young heroes,\" the Oracle says, her voice echoing strangely, \"I have foreseen your coming. The goddess Athena's sacred owl has been stolen by a mischievous creature and hidden somewhere in the mythological realm. You must retrieve it before the next full moon, or wisdom will fade from the world.\"\n\nShe hands you a golden thread. \"This is Ariadne's thread, a gift that once helped the hero Theseus escape a labyrinth. It will guide you home when your quest is complete.\"\n\n*Fun Fact: The Oracle at Delphi was one of the most important religious sites in ancient Greece. People traveled from far away to ask the Oracle questions about their future!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Ask the Oracle which god might help us",
          "nextNodeId": "ask-about-gods"
        },
        {
          "text": "Ask about the creature that stole the owl",
          "nextNodeId": "ask-about-thief"
        },
        {
          "text": "Set off immediately toward Mount Olympus",
          "nextNodeId": "journey-begins"
        }
      ]
    },
    "ask-about-gods": {
      "id": "ask-about-gods",
      "text": "\"A wise question,\" the Oracle nods. \"The twelve Olympian gods each have their own personalities and powers. Zeus rules as king of the gods with his thunderbolts. Poseidon commands the seas. Hades governs the underworld.\"\n\nShe continues, \"Athena herself is the goddess of wisdom and strategic warfare. Her rival is Ares, the god of violent war. Hermes, the messenger god with his winged sandals, might be helpful - he knows all the secret paths.\"\n\n\"And remember,\" she adds with a mysterious smile, \"the gods appreciate offerings and respect. They frown upon hubris - excessive pride. Many heroes have fallen because they thought themselves equal to the gods.\"\n\n*Greek Mythology: The Greeks believed twelve major gods lived on Mount Olympus. They were called the Olympians!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Seek out Hermes for help with the journey",
          "nextNodeId": "find-hermes"
        },
        {
          "text": "Visit Athena's temple to learn more",
          "nextNodeId": "athena-temple"
        },
        {
          "text": "Set off on your quest now",
          "nextNodeId": "journey-begins"
        }
      ]
    },
    "ask-about-thief": {
      "id": "ask-about-thief",
      "text": "The Oracle's eyes seem to cloud over with visions. \"The thief is crafty and ancient - a Sphinx, the creature with a lion's body, eagle's wings, and a human head. She loves riddles more than anything.\"\n\n\"Long ago, a Sphinx guarded the city of Thebes and asked travelers a riddle. Those who answered wrong were devoured! Only the hero Oedipus solved her puzzle.\"\n\nShe leans closer. \"This Sphinx has hidden the owl somewhere in the mythological realm, protected by riddles and challenges. You will need both cleverness and courage.\"\n\n*Mythology Fact: The most famous riddle of the Sphinx was: 'What walks on four legs in the morning, two legs at noon, and three legs in the evening?' The answer is a human - crawling as a baby, walking as an adult, and using a cane in old age!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Practice solving riddles before leaving",
          "nextNodeId": "riddle-practice"
        },
        {
          "text": "Search for the Sphinx directly",
          "nextNodeId": "journey-begins"
        }
      ]
    },
    "riddle-practice": {
      "id": "riddle-practice",
      "text": "A temple priest offers to help you practice. \"Riddles require thinking differently,\" he explains. \"Listen carefully to every word - the answer is always hidden in the question itself.\"\n\nHe poses a riddle: \"I have cities, but no houses live there. I have mountains, but no trees grow. I have water, but no fish swim. What am I?\"\n\n{{PLAYER1_NAME}} thinks hard. \"Cities without houses... mountains without trees...\"\n\n\"A map!\" {{PLAYER2_NAME}} exclaims. \"It's a map!\"\n\nThe priest beams. \"Excellent! You think like true heroes. Remember - myths are full of clever puzzles. The answer often isn't what it first seems.\"\n\n*Critical Thinking: Ancient Greeks valued wisdom highly. They believed clever thinking was just as heroic as physical strength!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Ask for one more practice riddle",
          "nextNodeId": "second-riddle"
        },
        {
          "text": "Feel ready and begin the quest",
          "nextNodeId": "journey-begins"
        }
      ]
    },
    "second-riddle": {
      "id": "second-riddle",
      "text": "\"Very well,\" the priest says. \"Here's a trickier one: I am not alive, yet I grow. I don't have lungs, but I need air. I don't have a mouth, but water kills me. What am I?\"\n\nYou both puzzle over this one. Not alive but grows... needs air... water kills it...\n\n\"Fire!\" you both say together.\n\n\"You're ready,\" the priest nods approvingly. \"The Sphinx will find you worthy opponents. One last piece of advice: in Greek myths, things are often not what they appear. A monster might become a friend, and a friend might become a challenge.\"\n\n*Learning Point: Fire was one of the most important discoveries for early humans. The Greek myth of Prometheus tells how he stole fire from the gods to give to humanity!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Thank the priest and begin your journey",
          "nextNodeId": "journey-begins"
        }
      ]
    },
    "find-hermes": {
      "id": "find-hermes",
      "text": "You decide to seek Hermes, the messenger god. Following the Oracle's directions, you climb a winding path up Mount Olympus until you reach a crossroads marked with a stone pillar.\n\nSuddenly, a young man appears in a flash of light! He has winged sandals on his feet and a winged helmet on his head. In his hand, he carries a staff with two snakes wrapped around it.\n\n\"Looking for me?\" Hermes grins mischievously. \"I am Hermes, god of travelers, thieves, and messengers. I heard about your quest - sounds entertaining!\"\n\n*Greek God Facts: Hermes' staff is called a caduceus. His winged sandals are called talaria, and they let him fly faster than the wind!*\n\n\"I'll tell you a secret,\" he whispers. \"The Sphinx has hidden the owl in the Labyrinth of Crete. But to enter, you'll need the blessing of one of the gods.\"",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Ask Hermes for his blessing",
          "nextNodeId": "hermes-blessing"
        },
        {
          "text": "Ask how to get to Crete",
          "nextNodeId": "journey-to-crete"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hermes-blessing": {
      "id": "hermes-blessing",
      "text": "\"My blessing?\" Hermes laughs, his eyes twinkling. \"I like you two! You've got spirit. Very well - I'll give you a gift.\"\n\nHe touches your foreheads, and suddenly you feel lighter on your feet. \"I've given you the traveler's blessing. You'll never get lost on roads, and you'll always find shelter when you need it.\"\n\nHe also hands you a small vial. \"This is nectar, the drink of the gods. One sip will heal any wound. Use it wisely - there's only enough for one use.\"\n\n\"Now, to reach the Labyrinth, you must travel to the island of Crete. You can sail there or... I know a shortcut through the Underworld. It's faster but more dangerous.\"\n\n*Mythology: Nectar and ambrosia were the food and drink of the Greek gods. Mortals who consumed them were said to become immortal!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Take the safe route by ship to Crete",
          "nextNodeId": "sail-to-crete"
        },
        {
          "text": "Risk the shortcut through the Underworld",
          "nextNodeId": "enter-underworld"
        }
      ]
    },
    "athena-temple": {
      "id": "athena-temple",
      "text": "You travel to Athens, the great city named after the goddess Athena. The Parthenon, her magnificent temple, sits atop the Acropolis - a hill in the center of the city.\n\nInside the temple stands a towering statue of Athena, forty feet tall, made of gold and ivory. Her grey eyes seem to watch you.\n\n\"Goddess Athena,\" {{PLAYER1_NAME}} says respectfully, \"we seek your sacred owl. A Sphinx has stolen it. Please help us.\"\n\nThe statue's eyes glow, and a voice fills your minds: \"Brave young ones. My owl, symbol of wisdom, must be returned. I shall give you gifts for your journey.\"\n\nA shield and a scroll appear before you. \"The shield shows the truth in reflections. The scroll contains one answer to any question - use it wisely.\"\n\n*Architecture: The Parthenon was built around 447-432 BCE. It's considered one of the greatest examples of ancient Greek architecture!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Ask Athena where to find the Sphinx",
          "nextNodeId": "athena-advice"
        },
        {
          "text": "Thank her and begin searching",
          "nextNodeId": "journey-begins"
        }
      ]
    },
    "athena-advice": {
      "id": "athena-advice",
      "text": "\"The Sphinx dwells in the ancient Labyrinth of Crete,\" Athena's voice echoes. \"It was built by Daedalus, the greatest inventor of the age, to contain the Minotaur - a monster with a bull's head and human body.\"\n\n\"The hero Theseus defeated the Minotaur long ago, but the Labyrinth remains, full of twists, traps, and new dangers. The Sphinx now uses it as her home.\"\n\n\"Remember,\" the goddess adds, \"wisdom is not just knowledge - it is knowing when to fight and when to think. Not all monsters need to be battled. Some puzzles are solved with words, not swords.\"\n\n*The Minotaur: In mythology, King Minos of Crete kept the Minotaur in the Labyrinth and fed it human sacrifices until Theseus killed it!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Travel to the island of Crete",
          "nextNodeId": "journey-to-crete"
        },
        {
          "text": "Ask about Daedalus the inventor",
          "nextNodeId": "learn-about-daedalus"
        }
      ]
    },
    "learn-about-daedalus": {
      "id": "learn-about-daedalus",
      "text": "\"Daedalus,\" Athena says with admiration, \"was my favorite mortal inventor. He created wonders that seemed like magic - living statues, mechanical servants, and the famous Labyrinth.\"\n\n\"When King Minos trapped Daedalus on Crete, he built wings from feathers and wax for himself and his son Icarus. But Icarus flew too close to the sun, the wax melted, and he fell into the sea.\"\n\n\"The lesson of Icarus is important: follow wise advice and don't let excitement make you reckless. This applies to your quest too. The Labyrinth is full of temptations and distractions.\"\n\n*The Story of Icarus: This myth teaches about the danger of ignoring warnings and being too ambitious. 'Don't fly too close to the sun' is still a saying we use today!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Keep this lesson in mind and journey to Crete",
          "nextNodeId": "journey-to-crete"
        }
      ]
    },
    "journey-begins": {
      "id": "journey-begins",
      "text": "You set off from Delphi, climbing down the mountain paths. The ancient world spreads before you - olive groves, white-columned temples, and distant blue seas.\n\n\"Look!\" {{PLAYER2_NAME}} points at the sky. A magnificent chariot pulled by flaming horses streaks across the heavens - it's Helios, the sun god, driving the sun across the sky as he does every day.\n\nYou reach a fork in the road. One path leads toward the harbor and ships to Crete. The other winds toward a dark forest where, according to legend, many magical creatures dwell.\n\n*Daily Mythology: The Greeks believed Helios drove his sun chariot from east to west every day, and traveled underground at night to return to the east!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Head to the harbor to sail to Crete",
          "nextNodeId": "journey-to-crete"
        },
        {
          "text": "Explore the mysterious forest",
          "nextNodeId": "enchanted-forest"
        }
      ]
    },
    "journey-to-crete": {
      "id": "journey-to-crete",
      "text": "You reach the harbor and find a ship preparing to sail to Crete. The captain, a weathered sailor, agrees to take you.\n\n\"Mind Poseidon's temper,\" he warns, looking at the sea nervously. \"The god of the ocean is unpredictable. We must make an offering before we sail.\"\n\nHe pours wine into the sea and prays. Soon, the sails catch wind, and you're off across the sparkling Aegean Sea.\n\nHalfway across, the ship lurches! Rising from the waves is a beautiful woman with a fish's tail - a nereid, one of the sea nymphs.\n\n\"Travelers!\" she calls. \"I am Thetis, mother of the hero Achilles. I sense a noble quest. How may I help?\"\n\n*Greek Mythology: Nereids were fifty sea nymph sisters who helped sailors. Thetis was the most famous - she dipped her son Achilles in the River Styx to make him invincible (except his heel, where she held him)!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Ask Thetis about the Labyrinth's dangers",
          "nextNodeId": "thetis-warning"
        },
        {
          "text": "Ask about her famous son Achilles",
          "nextNodeId": "achilles-story"
        },
        {
          "text": "Thank her and continue sailing",
          "nextNodeId": "arrive-crete"
        }
      ]
    },
    "thetis-warning": {
      "id": "thetis-warning",
      "text": "Thetis's expression grows serious. \"The Labyrinth holds three trials before you can face the Sphinx. First, you'll meet the Sirens - creatures whose beautiful singing lures travelers to their doom. Cover your ears or find another way past.\"\n\n\"Second, you'll face a choice between two paths - one guarded by Scylla, a six-headed monster, and one by Charybdis, a deadly whirlpool. Neither is safe, but one is survivable.\"\n\n\"Finally, you must answer the Sphinx's riddle. Fail, and you'll be trapped in the Labyrinth forever.\"\n\nShe gives you each a seashell. \"Blow these if you're ever in danger near water. My sisters and I will come.\"\n\n*Scylla and Charybdis: This phrase 'between Scylla and Charybdis' still means choosing between two bad options. We also say 'between a rock and a hard place'!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Thank Thetis and sail onward",
          "nextNodeId": "arrive-crete"
        }
      ]
    },
    "achilles-story": {
      "id": "achilles-story",
      "text": "Thetis smiles sadly. \"My son Achilles was the greatest warrior who ever lived. When he was a baby, I dipped him in the River Styx to make him invincible. But I held him by his heel, which the water never touched.\"\n\n\"He fought in the Trojan War and defeated countless enemies. But an arrow struck his heel - his only weakness - and he died.\"\n\n\"This is why we call a weakness an 'Achilles' heel,'\" she explains. \"Everyone has one. Even monsters. Even the Sphinx. Find her weakness, and you will succeed.\"\n\n{{PLAYER1_NAME}} asks, \"What was the Trojan War?\"\n\n\"A great war between Greece and Troy, fought over the beautiful Helen. Perhaps another time I'll tell you that tale!\"\n\n*Vocabulary: 'Achilles' heel' means a person's weakness. It comes directly from this Greek myth!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Ask about the Labyrinth",
          "nextNodeId": "thetis-warning"
        },
        {
          "text": "Thank her and continue to Crete",
          "nextNodeId": "arrive-crete"
        }
      ]
    },
    "enchanted-forest": {
      "id": "enchanted-forest",
      "text": "The forest is dense and magical. Strange flowers glow with soft light, and you hear distant music.\n\n\"These are the woods of the nymphs,\" {{PLAYER2_NAME}} whispers. \"Nature spirits who protect the wild places.\"\n\nYou come upon a clearing where a half-man, half-horse creature plays a reed pipe. It's a centaur!\n\n\"Young travelers!\" he greets you, stopping his music. \"I am Chiron, teacher of heroes. I trained Hercules, Achilles, and many others. What brings you to my forest?\"\n\n*Centaurs: While most centaurs in Greek myths were wild and dangerous, Chiron was wise and kind. He taught medicine, music, and combat to many famous heroes!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Tell Chiron about your quest",
          "nextNodeId": "chiron-teaches"
        },
        {
          "text": "Ask about the heroes he trained",
          "nextNodeId": "hero-stories"
        }
      ]
    },
    "chiron-teaches": {
      "id": "chiron-teaches",
      "text": "Chiron listens carefully to your tale. \"The Sphinx's riddles test wisdom, but her true challenge tests character. Many heroes fail because they rely only on strength.\"\n\nHe leads you to a target range. \"Let me teach you what I taught Hercules - that every problem has multiple solutions.\"\n\nHe demonstrates how to solve problems: sometimes with force, sometimes with cleverness, sometimes with kindness. \"The greatest heroes know when to use each approach.\"\n\nBefore you leave, he gives you a lyre - a stringed instrument. \"Music has power in the mythological world. Play this, and even monsters may pause to listen.\"\n\n*Hercules: The strongest hero in Greek mythology! He completed twelve 'impossible' labors, including defeating the Nemean Lion and capturing the three-headed dog Cerberus.*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Continue to the harbor for Crete",
          "nextNodeId": "journey-to-crete"
        },
        {
          "text": "Ask about Hercules' labors",
          "nextNodeId": "hercules-labors"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hero-stories": {
      "id": "hero-stories",
      "text": "Chiron's eyes sparkle with memories. \"Hercules was my strongest student - he could wrestle lions! But he had to learn that strength alone doesn't solve everything.\"\n\n\"Achilles was the fastest and most skilled warrior, but his pride sometimes clouded his judgment.\"\n\n\"And young Jason, who led the Argonauts to find the Golden Fleece - he succeeded because he worked with his team, not despite them.\"\n\nHe looks at both of you. \"You are two heroes working together. That is your greatest advantage. The Sphinx will try to divide you with her tricks. Stay united.\"\n\n*The Argonauts: Jason's crew of heroes who sailed on the ship Argo. They included Hercules, Orpheus (a magical musician), and Atalanta (a fierce huntress).*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Promise to work together and head to Crete",
          "nextNodeId": "journey-to-crete"
        }
      ]
    },
    "hercules-labors": {
      "id": "hercules-labors",
      "text": "\"The Twelve Labors!\" Chiron chuckles. \"King Eurystheus gave Hercules twelve 'impossible' tasks as punishment. But Hercules completed them all!\"\n\n\"He defeated the Nemean Lion, whose fur couldn't be pierced by weapons. He captured the Golden Hind of Artemis without harming it. He cleaned the Augean Stables - which hadn't been cleaned in thirty years - in a single day by diverting two rivers!\"\n\n\"My favorite was when he had to get the golden apples of the Hesperides. Instead of fighting, he tricked Atlas into getting them for him. Brains over brawn!\"\n\n\"Remember: when facing impossible challenges, there's always a clever solution.\"\n\n*Problem Solving: The Greeks valued 'metis' - cunning intelligence. Sometimes the smartest solution is the one no one expects!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Thank Chiron and head to Crete",
          "nextNodeId": "journey-to-crete"
        }
      ]
    },
    "sail-to-crete": {
      "id": "sail-to-crete",
      "text": "With Hermes' blessing, your sea voyage is smooth. The winds favor you, and dolphins race alongside the ship - a sign of good luck from Poseidon.\n\nAs Crete appears on the horizon, you see its famous landmark: Mount Ida, where legend says baby Zeus was hidden from his father Kronos in a cave.\n\n\"There!\" the captain points to a rocky coastline. \"The entrance to the Labyrinth is in those cliffs. May the gods protect you!\"\n\nYou thank him and swim to shore. Before you stands an ancient doorway carved into the rock, decorated with maze patterns and images of the Minotaur.\n\n*Baby Zeus: The Titan Kronos ate his children because of a prophecy that one would overthrow him. Zeus' mother hid him in Crete, where he grew up to defeat Kronos and free his siblings!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Enter the Labyrinth",
          "nextNodeId": "labyrinth-entrance"
        }
      ]
    },
    "enter-underworld": {
      "id": "enter-underworld",
      "text": "Hermes leads you to a dark cave. \"This entrance leads to the Underworld, the realm of Hades. Stay close and don't stray from the path.\"\n\nYou descend into darkness until you reach a vast underground river - the Styx. A hooded figure waits in a boat: Charon, the ferryman of the dead.\n\n\"Living mortals?\" Charon croaks. \"You must pay the toll - two gold coins each.\"\n\nHermes hands him the coins. \"These children are on a quest approved by the gods.\"\n\nAs you cross, you see ghostly shapes in the mist - the spirits of the dead. It's eerie but not frightening. They seem peaceful.\n\n*The River Styx: Ancient Greeks buried their dead with coins under their tongues to pay Charon. Without payment, souls had to wander for a hundred years!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Ask Charon about the Underworld",
          "nextNodeId": "underworld-tour"
        },
        {
          "text": "Hurry through quickly",
          "nextNodeId": "underworld-exit"
        }
      ]
    },
    "underworld-tour": {
      "id": "underworld-tour",
      "text": "\"The Underworld has many regions,\" Charon explains in his raspy voice. \"Elysium is paradise for heroes and the virtuous. Tartarus is a pit of punishment for the wicked.\"\n\n\"Most souls go to the Asphodel Meadows - a gray, neutral place for ordinary people who did neither great good nor great evil.\"\n\nHe points to a massive three-headed dog guarding a gate. \"That's Cerberus. He lets souls in but none out. Well, except for Hercules, who borrowed him once. And Orpheus, who charmed him with music.\"\n\n{{PLAYER2_NAME}} remembers the lyre Chiron gave you. Music might be useful here...\n\n*Cerberus: The three-headed dog guards the entrance to the Underworld. His name might mean 'spotted' - so the Greeks basically named their terrifying hellhound 'Spot'!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Exit to Crete quickly",
          "nextNodeId": "underworld-exit"
        }
      ]
    },
    "underworld-exit": {
      "id": "underworld-exit",
      "text": "Hermes guides you through a secret passage that spirals upward. \"This path connects to the Labyrinth of Crete. Few know it exists.\"\n\nYou climb for what feels like hours until you see light ahead. You emerge inside a massive stone corridor - you're in the Labyrinth!\n\n\"This is where I leave you,\" Hermes says. \"Remember: the Labyrinth is designed to confuse. Trust your Ariadne's thread. And don't forget - I gave you the traveler's blessing. You'll find your way.\"\n\nWith a wink and a flash, he disappears.\n\nThe corridor stretches in two directions. Strange echoes bounce off the walls.\n\n*The Labyrinth: Daedalus designed it to be so confusing that no one who entered could find their way out. Even he barely escaped from his own creation!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Go left toward a faint singing sound",
          "nextNodeId": "siren-chamber"
        },
        {
          "text": "Go right toward scratch marks on the walls",
          "nextNodeId": "beast-corridor"
        }
      ]
    },
    "arrive-crete": {
      "id": "arrive-crete",
      "text": "Your ship lands on the rocky shores of Crete. The island is beautiful - olive trees, white buildings, and the massive ruins of the ancient Palace of Knossos.\n\n\"The Labyrinth entrance is below the palace,\" the captain tells you. \"King Minos built it long ago. Be careful - the maze changes, they say. Walls shift when you're not looking.\"\n\nYou climb up to the palace ruins. Sure enough, beneath a crumbling archway, you find stairs leading down into darkness. Cool air rises from below, carrying the smell of ancient stone.\n\n{{PLAYER1_NAME}} ties the Ariadne's thread to a pillar. \"This will lead us back out.\"\n\n*The Palace of Knossos: This real place in Crete was excavated in 1900! Some historians think the palace's complicated layout inspired the Labyrinth myth.*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Descend into the Labyrinth",
          "nextNodeId": "labyrinth-entrance"
        }
      ]
    },
    "labyrinth-entrance": {
      "id": "labyrinth-entrance",
      "text": "The Labyrinth is vast and ancient. Torches on the walls light themselves as you approach and dim after you pass. The corridors twist and turn in impossible ways.\n\nOn the walls, you see paintings depicting Greek myths - Perseus defeating Medusa, Orpheus descending to save Eurydice, Theseus battling the Minotaur.\n\n\"These stories are clues,\" {{PLAYER2_NAME}} realizes. \"They're showing us how other heroes succeeded!\"\n\nAhead, the corridor splits three ways. From one comes beautiful singing. From another, you hear something large breathing. The third is completely silent.\n\n*Hero Patterns: Greek myths often follow patterns - heroes receive magical items, face trials, and must use cleverness as much as strength!*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Follow the beautiful singing",
          "nextNodeId": "siren-chamber"
        },
        {
          "text": "Investigate the breathing sound",
          "nextNodeId": "beast-corridor"
        },
        {
          "text": "Take the silent path",
          "nextNodeId": "trap-corridor"
        }
      ]
    },
    "siren-chamber": {
      "id": "siren-chamber",
      "text": "You follow the singing and enter a chamber decorated with seashells and pearls. Three beautiful women sit on rocks, singing a melody so lovely that {{PLAYER1_NAME}} starts walking toward them in a daze.\n\n\"Sirens!\" {{PLAYER2_NAME}} remembers. \"Their song enchants people! We need to block our ears!\"\n\nBut the Sirens' song shifts, singing directly to {{PLAYER2_NAME}} now: \"Stay and listen... rest here forever...\"\n\nYou remember what you learned - Odysseus tied himself to his ship's mast to hear the Sirens without going to them. There must be another way past!\n\n*The Sirens: In Homer's Odyssey, the hero Odysseus had his sailors plug their ears with beeswax while he was tied to the mast, so he could hear the Sirens' song without being lured to his death.*",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Cover your ears and run past",
